# Topic 4: CSS Layouts — Building Responsive Pages (Roadmap Checklist)

## Level 1 — Beginner: Normal flow, and the tools that deviate from it

- [ ] **Understand normal flow first, because every layout technique is defined relative to it.** By default, with no layout CSS applied at all, block-level elements (`div`, `p`, `section`) stack top to bottom, and inline elements (`a`, `span`) flow left to right within a line, wrapping like text. This default behavior is great for documents but completely inadequate for arranging UI side by side, centering things, or building equal-height columns — which is exactly the gap every layout system covered here exists to fill.
- [ ] **Understand `display` as the property that changes how an element participates in layout.** `block` and `inline` are the two defaults already described above; `inline-block` behaves inline but allows block-like sizing; `none` removes the element from layout entirely (it takes up no space); `flex` and `grid` don't just style the element itself — they switch on an entirely different layout *mode* for its direct children.
- [ ] **Learn the five values of `position` and what each actually removes the element from or anchors it to:** `static` (default, normal flow, the other values do nothing without changing this first), `relative` (the element stays in normal flow but can be visually offset from its original spot, and that original space is still reserved), `absolute` (the element is pulled completely out of normal flow and positioned relative to its nearest *positioned* ancestor instead), `fixed` (positioned relative to the viewport itself, so it stays in place during scrolling), `sticky` (behaves like `relative` until a scroll threshold is crossed, then behaves like `fixed`).
- [ ] **Learn the historical role of `float`, so you understand it rather than just avoid it.** `float` was originally built for one purpose only — letting text wrap around an image, like a magazine layout. For years, before Flexbox and Grid existed, developers repurposed it to build entire page layouts because there was nothing better, which produced a lot of fragile workarounds (like "clearfix" hacks). It's still correct for its *original* purpose; it's just no longer the right tool for general layout.
- [ ] **Learn Flexbox's two core ideas: a main axis and a cross axis.** Once a container has `display: flex`, its children align along a main axis (controlled by `justify-content`) and a cross axis perpendicular to it (controlled by `align-items`); `flex-direction: row` (default) makes the main axis horizontal, `flex-direction: column` makes it vertical.
- [ ] **Learn Grid's two core properties:** `grid-template-columns` and `grid-template-rows` explicitly define the columns and rows of a grid all at once, and `gap` adds consistent spacing between tracks without needing margin hacks on individual items.
- [ ] **Learn the basic `@media` query syntax** — `@media (min-width: 768px) { ... }` wraps a block of CSS that only applies when the condition is true — and learn that the `<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">` tag in `<head>` is not optional boilerplate: without it, mobile browsers render at a desktop-width virtual viewport and just zoom out, making your media queries effectively meaningless.
- [ ] **Hands-on:** build the same simple three-box layout three different ways — first with floats, then with Flexbox, then with Grid — purely to feel viscerally how much more direct Flexbox and Grid are for the exact same visual outcome.

## Level 2 — Intermediate: How Flexbox and Grid actually distribute space

- [ ] **Understand `flex-grow`, `flex-shrink`, and `flex-basis` as the real engine behind Flexbox**, not just `justify-content`/`align-items`. The core idea: each flex item starts at `flex-basis` size, then any *leftover* space in the container gets distributed proportionally according to each item's `flex-grow` value, and if items collectively *overflow* the container, the shrinkage is distributed according to `flex-shrink`. Flexbox is, at its heart, an algorithm for distributing available space along one axis — everything else is convenience syntax around that one idea.
- [ ] **Learn `flex-wrap`.** By default flex items are forced onto a single line even if they overflow; `flex-wrap: wrap` lets them flow onto additional lines instead, and each resulting line then behaves like its own mini flex container for cross-axis alignment purposes.
- [ ] **Learn the single most common real-world Flexbox pattern: perfect centering.** `display: flex; justify-content: center; align-items: center;` on a container centers its child both horizontally and vertically — a problem that was notoriously fiddly before Flexbox existed, which is a big part of why Flexbox adoption spread so fast.
- [ ] **Learn Grid's more advanced placement tools:** `grid-template-areas` lets you name layout regions in a readable, almost-ASCII-art way (`"header header" "sidebar main"`) instead of only thinking in raw row/column numbers; the `fr` unit represents a fraction of *remaining* space (conceptually Grid's equivalent of `flex-grow`); and `grid-column: span 2` / `grid-row: span 2` let an individual item deliberately occupy multiple tracks at once.
- [ ] **Understand the explicit vs. implicit grid distinction.** The explicit grid is whatever you defined with `grid-template-columns`/`rows`; if you place more items than that grid has room for, the browser automatically generates additional implicit tracks to hold the overflow, using rules you can influence via `grid-auto-rows`/`grid-auto-columns`.
- [ ] **Internalize the real decision rule for choosing Flexbox vs. Grid, from first principles, not preference.** Flexbox is fundamentally **one-dimensional** — it excels at distributing items along a single row or column. Grid is fundamentally **two-dimensional** — it excels when you need to control rows *and* columns simultaneously as one coordinated system. A navbar (one row of items) is a textbook Flexbox case; a page layout with a header, sidebar, main content, and footer (multiple rows and columns interacting) is a textbook Grid case. This single distinction resolves the vast majority of "which one do I use here" hesitation.
- [ ] **Learn mobile-first methodology, and why it's the prevailing approach, not just a convention.** Mobile-first means writing your base (unconditional) CSS for the smallest/simplest viewport first, then layering *additional* complexity on top using `min-width` media queries as the screen grows. The first-principles reason this tends to work better than the reverse (desktop-first with `max-width` queries scaling down): it forces you to decide what's actually essential content first, and it avoids the common desktop-first trap of writing elaborate styles that then need to be partially undone/overridden repeatedly at each smaller breakpoint.

## Level 3 — Expert: Edge cases, intrinsic responsiveness, and accessibility traps

- [ ] **Understand the exact rule for what `position: absolute` is positioned relative to, since misreading this is one of the most common real-world layout bugs.** An absolutely positioned element is placed relative to its *nearest ancestor* that has any `position` value other than `static` (i.e., `relative`, `absolute`, `fixed`, or `sticky`) — if no ancestor qualifies, it falls all the way back to being positioned relative to the initial containing block (effectively the page). "I set `position: relative` on the wrong wrapper" is an extremely common debugging session caused directly by this rule.
- [ ] **Learn `minmax()` combined with `repeat(auto-fit, ...)` or `repeat(auto-fill, ...)` as a genuinely different responsive philosophy than media queries.** `grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr))` tells the grid itself to figure out how many columns fit, each at least 200px wide, growing to fill remaining space — with zero explicit breakpoints at all. This is "intrinsically responsive" layout: the layout reacts to available space directly, rather than reacting to a fixed set of screen-width thresholds you had to predict in advance.
- [ ] **Know that CSS Grid Level 2 introduces subgrid**, letting a nested grid inherit and align to its parent grid's tracks — solving the previously awkward problem of getting nested grid items to line up with the outer grid's columns/rows without duplicating the track definitions.
- [ ] **Know about container queries as the evolution beyond media queries for component-based design.** A media query only knows about the *viewport*; it has no idea how much space a specific component actually has, which breaks down once you build reusable components that might be narrow in a sidebar and wide in a main column on the very same page. Container queries (`@container`) let a component style itself based on the size of its own containing element instead — the more correct tool once you're thinking in components rather than pages.
- [ ] **Understand the real performance distinction:** Flexbox and Grid layout calculations are generally more computationally expensive per element than simple block flow, because the browser has to solve a space-distribution algorithm rather than just stack boxes — usually irrelevant, but worth knowing if you're ever rendering layouts with thousands of dynamically positioned items.
- [ ] **Understand the accessibility trap hidden inside visual reordering.** Flexbox's `order` property (and Grid's placement properties) can visually rearrange items completely independently of their actual order in the HTML/DOM. Screen readers and keyboard tab order still follow DOM order, not visual order — so using `order` purely for visual effect can silently create a mismatch where the screen-reader/keyboard experience no longer matches what's visually presented, confusing exactly the users who rely on non-visual navigation most.
- [ ] **Know the newer viewport units (`dvh`, `svh`, `lvh`) exist to solve a specific mobile pain point** — the classic `vh` unit historically measured the viewport *including* space that mobile browser chrome (address bar, toolbars) might dynamically show or hide, causing layouts to jump; the newer dynamic/small/large viewport units give explicit control over which of those states you're actually sizing against.
- [ ] **Hands-on:** build a responsive navbar with Flexbox that switches to a stacked layout under a mobile-first media query; build a card grid using `repeat(auto-fit, minmax(...))` and resize the browser window to watch it reflow with zero media queries; deliberately use `order` to visually reverse two items, then tab through them with the keyboard to witness the DOM-order-vs-visual-order mismatch for yourself.

## Quick self-check before moving on

You should be able to explain, without looking anything up: why normal flow alone can't build most real UI layouts, the actual rule for what `position: absolute` anchors to, why "one-dimensional vs. two-dimensional" is the real deciding factor between Flexbox and Grid, why mobile-first is generally favored over desktop-first, and why visually reordering elements with `order` can quietly break accessibility even when it looks fine.